\end_inset

Stevens operators are denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{k,q}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0,1,\dots$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q=-k,\dots k$
\end_inset

.
 An alternative terminology is to denote these as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sine/cosine
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 operators, which correspond to negative/nonnegative 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 values,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{k,q}\equiv\begin{cases}
\mathcal{O}_{k,|q|}^{s} & (-k\leq q<0)\\
\mathcal{O}_{k,|q|}^{c} & (0\leq q\leq k)
\end{cases}.
\]

\end_inset

The Stevens operators are perhaps best understood as a symmetrization of
 the spherical tensor operators.
 By the Wigner-Eckhart theorem, spherical tensors must have matrix elements
 proportional to the Clebsch Gordon coefficients
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(T_{q}^{k}\right)_{m,m'}\propto\langle jm'kq|jm\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

involving angular momentum states 
\begin_inset Formula $|jm\rangle$
\end_inset

 in the spin-
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 representation of SU(2).
 Equivalently, in terms of the Wigner 3-
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 symbol,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(T_{q}^{k}\right)_{m,m'}\propto(-1)^{-m}\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
j & k & j\\
-m & q & m'
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

The proportionality constant depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The indices 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m'$
\end_inset

 run over 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2j+1$
\end_inset

 possible values, {
\begin_inset Formula $-j,\dots j$
\end_inset

}.
 The integer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary, subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $k\leq2j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Koster and Statz (1959) and Buckmaster et al (1972) convention (KS/BCS),
 one defines
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(T_{q}^{k}\right)_{m,m'}=c_{k,j}(-1)^{j-m}\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
j & k & j\\
-m & q & m'
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{k,j}=k!\left\{ \frac{(2j+k+1)!}{(2k)!(2j-k)!}\right\} ^{1/2}.
\]

\end_inset

The Stevens operators are then defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{O}_{k,q}^{s} & =ia_{k,q}\left[T_{-q}-(-1)^{q}T_{q}\right],\\
\mathcal{O}_{k,q}^{c} & =a_{k,q}\left[T_{-q}+(-1)^{q}T_{q}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k,q}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\leq6$
\end_inset

 are given in Table 1 of C.
 Rudowicz, J.
 Phys.
 C: Solid State Phys.
 18, 1415 (1985),
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{k,q}=\left[\begin{array}{ccccccc}
1 & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\\
\sqrt{6} & \frac{1}{2} & 1\\
\sqrt{10} & \sqrt{\frac{10}{3}} & \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} & \sqrt{2}\\
2\sqrt{70} & \sqrt{\frac{7}{2}} & \sqrt{7} & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} & 2\\
6\sqrt{14} & 2\sqrt{\frac{21}{5}} & \sqrt{\frac{3}{5}} & 6\sqrt{\frac{2}{5}} & \frac{2}{\sqrt{5}} & 2\sqrt{2}\\
4\sqrt{231} & \sqrt{22} & 4\sqrt{\frac{11}{5}} & 2\sqrt{\frac{11}{5}} & 4\sqrt{\frac{11}{6}} & \frac{2}{\sqrt{3}} & 4
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, the same Stevens operators can be expressed as polynomials
 of the spin-
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 operators 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{x},J_{y},J_{z}$
\end_inset

.
 The operators 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are generators of SU(2), defined to satisfy the commutation relations 
\begin_inset Formula $[J_{\alpha},J_{\beta}]=i\epsilon_{\alpha\beta\gamma}J_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

.
 Here we are working with an irrep of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2j+1$
\end_inset

.
 For models with time-reversal symmetry, only even-power Stevens operators
 can enter the Hamiltonian.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Below are the Stevens operators for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\{2,4,6\}$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=J_{x}^{2}+J_{y}^{2}+J_{z}^{2}=j(j+1),
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\pm}=J_{x}\pm iJ_{y}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
